Missing Data

library(VIM)
library(mice)
library(psych)

Types of Missing Data

  • Missing completely at random (MCAR): the probability of a value being missing is unrelated to its value on that variable or by variables on any other variables

    • There is no way to predict what value would be missing; there is no systematic reason for it being missing
    • If values below or above a certain threshold are consistently missing (especially due to measurement limitations), this is not completely at random - you can predict that these values are most likely to be missing

  • Missing at random (MAR): the probability of a value being missing is unrelated to its value on that variable, with other variables being controlled

    • If a ceramic is broken you might be missing ceramic width and breakage could be due to wall thickness
    • If you have measurements about wall thickness, then the missingness of ceramic width can be considered missing at random

  • Missing not at random (MNAR): the data missing are related to unobserved/unmeasured data

    • If a ceramic is broken you might be missing ceramic width and breakage could be due to wall thickness
    • Due to preservation, you are not able to collect thickness - you have unobserved data = MNAR

Missing Data in R

  • R uses NA to represent missing data
  • If there is a missing value in a character column, it will be represented by ""
    • Either code NA in the spreadsheet before importing or include the argument na.exclude=="" in the read.csv() function

Handling Missing Data by Rows or Columns

  • Listwise deletion: eliminating missing values from the data by removing rows that contain the missing data

    • This is often the default for many R functions
    • Reduces the number of observations (which may be severe depending on your data set [think archaeology/bioarchaeology]) - thereby will impact your sample sizes for statistical analyses and increases your standard errors
    • Depending on the severity of data, this may preclude certain multivariate statistics

  • Pairwise deletion: the variable for which an observation is missing data is skipped over when calculating analyses using that variable; however, if the observation does contain other data, those data will be used rather than skipping everything like in listwise deletion

  • Deleting variables/columns: eliminating variables that contain a lot of missing data

    • This may help take care of the problem if certain variables are where missing data are concentrated
    • However, if you do this step before listwise deletion, it may help to take out variables that contain a lot of missing data to reduce the number of observations with missing data

If You Need to Remove Variables or Individuals Missing More than a Certain Proportion of Data

  • To avoid having too much estimated data (you do not necessarily want to have a preponderance of estimated data compared to actual collected data), you may need to remove variables/columns and/or observations/rows missing more than a particular proportion of data

Using the Mean or Median to Impute Data

  • A traditional approach is using the mean or the median of a variable as a replacement for missing data
  • This could be significantly biased if being used to impute a lot of missing data
  • This will also affect the variance of a variable (create greater homogeneity) as well asaffect its covariance with other variables

KNN Imputation

  • Recent research has shown kNN is a useful method for imputation for craniometric data, with research also applying it to odontometric data, as well (Adams et al. 2018; Rathmann et al. 2018)
  • Combines multiple variables into a distance measure to find cases that are similar to the one containing missing values
  • \( k \)-nearest neighbors are used for imputation
    • Previous research has suggested 5 (Kenyhercz and Passalacqua 2016; Kenyhercz et al. 2019) is adequate
    • Too high and now you are including observations that are not similar
    • Too low and you may be missing out on important information
  • Can be applied to continuous (use the metric = "mean" or "median“) and categorical (use the metric = "median"”) data
  • Can use either the median or the mean of the \( k \)-nearest neighbors to impute missing value (pay attentio to data type, sample size, outliers, etc.)
  • Must specify the number of neighbors you want to use to estimate the data

Hot Deck

  • Replaces the missing values with observations from a similar and complete individual
    • This similar individual is randomly selected or adjacent
  • Multivariate relationships are not considered
  • Data must be missing at random
  • Use domain_var to organize your data into groups
    • Use ord_var to sort by size of a variable within the groups (not using this argument = random selection within domain_var group, using this argument = sorts observations by domain_var group, sorts by ord_var variable and chooses the value below the missing observation)

Iterative Robust Model-based Imputation (IRMI)

  • Missing values are response variables, with present data used as predictors for the missing value
  • Can handle different data types (continuous, ordinal, nominal)
    • Linear regression estimates continuous data
    • Logistic regression estimates binary data
  • IRMI can estimate scores beyond what is possible in a scoring system
    • Kenyhercz et al. (2019) recommend changing any scores beyond what is possible to the highest possible (Ex: if a trait is scored from 0-5 and you get a 7 through IRMI, change it to 5)

Multivariate Imputation by Chained Equations

  • An equation is constructed for each variable that has missing values
  • This is then used to predict each case of a missing value within that variable
    • The equation predicts the value of the missing data, finds some number of observations that are not missing data that have a similar value to the predicted value, and randomly chooses one to replace the missing observation
  • This is repeated a \( n \) number of times, producing \( n \) number of data sets with imputed values
  • Does not make assumptions of underlying distributions
    • Unlike expectation-maximization algorithm imputation which assumes a multivariate normal distribution

  • Based on data missing at random

  • Types:

    • Predictive mean matching - continuous
    • Logistic regression - binary
    • Multinomial logit model - nominal
    • Ordered logit model - ordinal

Sample2 <- Sample[,-c(2:4)]

#Row

miss2 <- c()
for(i in 1:nrow(Sample2)) {if(length(which(is.na(Sample2[i,]))) > 0.25*ncol(Sample2)) miss2 <- append(miss2,i)}
Sample3 <- Sample2[-miss2,]

Using the Mean or Median to Impute Data

Sample.mean <- Sample

Sample.mean$GOL[is.na(Sample.mean$GOL)] <- mean(Sample.mean$GOL,na.rm = TRUE)
Sample.mean$NOL[is.na(Sample.mean$NOL)] <- mean(Sample.mean$NOL,na.rm = TRUE)

MorphSample.median <- MorphSample

MorphSample.median$METO[is.na(MorphSample.median$METO)] <- median(MorphSample.median$METO,na.rm = TRUE)
MorphSample.median$PTBL[is.na(MorphSample.median$PTBL)] <- median(MorphSample.median$PTBL,na.rm = TRUE)

KNN Imputation

kNN(data = , variable = , metric = , k = )

- data: data to be imputed
- variable: what variables to be imputed (can be left blank if indexed in data)
- metric: "mean" or "median"; uses the mean or median of the *n* closest neighbors for the imputed value
- k: the number of neighbors you want to set

library(VIM)

Sampleknn <- kNN(data = Sample[5:12], metric = "mean", k =5)

Hot Deck

hotdeck(data = , variable = , ord_var = , domain_var = )

- data: data to be imputed
- variable: what variables to be imputed (can be left blank if indexed in data)
- ord_var: the function will not impute these data, instead it will order the data according to the variables you put in this argument, and then the observation missing a value will use the value just below it to replace it
- domain_var: grouping variable

library(VIM)
Samplehd <- hotdeck(data = Sample, ord_var = "AUB", domain_var = "Sex")

Iterative Robust Model-based Imputation (IRMI)

irmi(x = , eps = , maxit = , init.method = )

- x: data to be imputed
- eps: threshold for convergency
- maxit: maximum number of iterations
- init.method: method to initialize imputation (kNN or median)

library(VIM)
Sampleirmi <- irmi(x = Sample[5:12], eps = 5, maxit = 1000, init.method = "kNN")

Multivariate Imputation by Chained Equations

  • Types:
    • Predictive mean matching - continuous
    • Logistic regression - binary
    • Multinomial logit model - nominal
    • Ordered logit model - ordinal

mice(data = , m = , method = , maxit = , print = , seed = )

- data = Data you are imputing
- m = the number of comparisons and data sets you want to create (the default is 5)
- method = "which method you want to use to calculate the imputation"
- maxit = the number of iterations you want to produce
- print = FALSE is default (does not print the iterations as they occur)
- seed = an arbitrary number that just ensures you get the same result every time you use that seed (otherwise the estimates are random)

#install.packages("mice")
library(mice)

Sample <- within(Sample, {
  SexCode <- NA
  SexCode[Sex == "M"]   <- 1
  SexCode[Sex == "F"]  <- 2
})

Samplemice <- mice(data = Sample[5:13], m = 5, method = "pmm", maxit = 1000, print=FALSE, seed = 1234)
summary(Samplemice)

plot(Samplemice)


#Purple points represent imputed data and blue dots represent observed data - should have a similar distribution
stripplot(Samplemice)

  • It is possible to isolate one of the imputed data sets; however, in general you want to run your interested analysis on all of them and then pool the results
  • Think of MICE as a Bayesian approach to imputation; rather than saying the imputed value is exactly 3.6, having the five data sets allows accommodation of error and sampling from multiple probability distributions
  • This range in error can then be incorporated into analyses
